choices.text:
The teacher gives a sticker every day for showing up on time (a fixed-ratio schedule: one sticker per day, every day), and a sticker every week for getting above 90% on three quizzes in a row (a fixed-ratio schedule for quiz performance). The key observation is that quiz performance increased significantly, but tardiness only decreased slightly.

Let’s analyze the options:

A. Variable ratio schedules create the strongest responses and behavior that is the least susceptible to extinction.  
→ This is true in general (e.g., gambling, reinforcement in addiction), but the teacher is using fixed-ratio schedules (not variable), so this doesn't explain the specific pattern.

B. The students had more intrinsic motivation to do well on quizzes than to show up on time.  
→ This is plausible. The behavior change (quiz performance) is strong, but tardiness is weak. This suggests that the students were more motivated by the quiz rewards (possibly because they see the academic value) than by the daily sticker. This explains why quiz performance improved more than punctuality. This choice directly accounts for the differential behavior change.

C. The students’ behavior change was stronger in response to a fixed-ratio schedule than it was to a continuous reinforcement schedule.  
→ This is not accurate. Fixed-ratio schedules are not compared to continuous reinforcement here. Also, continuous reinforcement would lead to rapid extinction, which isn’t the case. Moreover, the teacher is using fixed-ratio (daily and weekly), not comparing two types of schedules.

D. The students’ behavior change was stronger in response to a fixed-ratio schedule than it was to a variable-interval schedule.  
→ There is no mention of variable-interval schedules (e.g., random rewards). The teacher’s system is fixed-ratio, so this comparison is not supported.

The best explanation is that students were more intrinsically motivated to perform well on quizzes than to show up on time — thus, the academic performance improved more significantly.

The answer is (B)
